======================================================================
Part 3: At n=4, chi_A = 1 iff H(T) = 2*c3 + 1
======================================================================
  VERIFIED: H(T_4) = 2*c3 + 1 for ALL 64 tournaments
  This is equivalent to chi_A = 1 at n=4
  Since c3 in {0, 1}: H in {1, 3} — but wait, c3=2 gives T_4 cyclic with H=5

  c3 distribution at n=4: {0: 24, 1: 16, 2: 24}
  H values: {0: 1, 1: 3, 2: 5}

======================================================================
Part 4: H vs 2*c3 + 1 at n=5
======================================================================
  H(T_5) = 2*c3 + 1: FAILS 544/1024 times (53.1%)

======================================================================
Part 5: Recursive formula via n=4 identity
H(T[S_4]) = 2*c3(S_4) + 1 for ALL 4-subsets S_4
excess_4 = 2 * sum_{|S|=4} c3(S) = 2 * c3 * (n-3)
chi_A = 1 + 2*c3 - 2*c3*(n-3) + excess_5 - ...
======================================================================

